Preparing the Source Data and Project


Data Source

The first question that needs to be addressed is "Where can we find the raw data that we can process?".

I located the data on the Department of Environmental Conservation (DEC) main website. 

URL https://www.dec.ny.gov/cfmx/extapps/GasOil/help/

Scrolling down, you can select the type of data as shown in the image below.


Using their search engine, you can query the data as shown in the image below and click on the submit button.


Below is how the search result looks like. The result can be exported in XLS or CSV format


Per the requirement of this project, I need to demonstrate the ETL process using JSON as a source so I  exported the data

from the DEC website then converted it into the JSON file.

I have proved the completed JSON Data here so, no need to redo the work. However, if you are interested in finding the current insight,  you can retrieve the most current data and load it by converting the data yourself.


Converting XLS or CSV into JSON

There are several web services that could be used to convert excel data into JSON. To mention a few, we have:

https://mygeodata.cloud/converter/xlsx-to-json

https://csvjson.com/

However, I used  http://beautifytools.com/excel-to-json-converter.php

As shown below, data were exported as an excel document and then converted into JSON.


All the data for this project have been provided for your download using the icon at the top of this page or one shown below.



How to use the Document ( NewYorkOilAndGas.zip) that has been provided to you.

First, extract the zip file to the desired location on your pc.


Familiarize yourself with the files. The ReadMe.txt file is a good place to start. it explains what each folder contains.
